If word gets out
before we know what we're gonna do

273
00:18:05,138 --> 00:18:07,473
there's gonna be panic

274
00:18:07,607 --> 00:18:08,708
And it's gonna ruin any chance

275
00:18:08,808 --> 00:18:11,177
we might have of surprise
if we decide to hit them

276
00:18:11,277 --> 00:18:13,880
We're gonna need to
do a few things right away

277
00:18:13,980 --> 00:18:15,682
No Pierre

278
00:18:15,782 --> 00:18:17,984
He knows, the press knows

279
00:18:18,518 --> 00:18:20,286
And you're gonna have to
keep up your schedule

280
00:18:20,420 --> 00:18:22,288
Your movements
are followed too closely

281
00:18:22,388 --> 00:18:24,190
George Ball's
got a conference room at State

282
00:18:24,257 --> 00:18:25,058
Good

283
00:18:25,158 --> 00:18:26,759
You meet over there this afternoon

284
00:18:26,893 --> 00:18:29,329
We'll figure out a way to
sneak you guys back in here tonight

285
00:18:29,429 --> 00:18:32,298
I think we should
bring in Dean Acheson

286
00:18:33,399 --> 00:18:33,833
Ken

287
00:18:33,967 --> 00:18:37,804
he was fighting Soviets while we were
still playing ball together at school

288
00:18:39,372 --> 00:18:41,074
Find him, Kenny

289
00:18:42,142 --> 00:18:43,977
We're gonna need
all the help we can get

290
00:18:45,812 --> 00:18:47,981
Screw secrecy

291
00:18:52,352 --> 00:18:56,789
Try having that fat-ass, sit on your
lap all the way from Foggy Bottom

292
00:18:56,856 --> 00:18:59,859
You were excited. I say no more

293
00:18:59,993 --> 00:19:02,695
Everybody agrees
the diplomatic route won't work

294
00:19:02,795 --> 00:19:05,765
It's too slow and they'll finish the
missiles while we're still talking

295
00:19:06,232 --> 00:19:09,802
I hear old Warren Harding
used to get his grills in through here

296
00:19:09,936 --> 00:19:12,772
We have 850 planes
assembling at Homestead

297
00:19:12,906 --> 00:19:18,611
Eglin, Opa Locka, MacDill
Partick, Pensacola, and Key West

298
00:19:19,445 --> 00:19:21,381
Due to the tropical foliage

299
00:19:21,514 --> 00:19:24,150
the OPLAN calls for high explosive

300
00:19:24,184 --> 00:19:25,919
and napalm loadouts
for our ground attack sorties

301
00:19:25,985 --> 00:19:28,488
I still think
there are diplomatic approaches

302
00:19:28,655 --> 00:19:29,756
we haven't considered yet

303
00:19:29,856 --> 00:19:31,825
Peace at any price?

304
00:19:31,891 --> 00:19:33,626
We have a gun to our head

305
00:19:34,460 --> 00:19:38,231
We have high confidence in the expanded
air strike option, Mr. President

306
00:19:38,364 --> 00:19:39,732
The problem, sir

307
00:19:39,833 --> 00:19:42,135
is that it's a short-term solution

308
00:19:42,268 --> 00:19:44,804
Kruschev can send in
more missiles next month

309
00:19:44,971 --> 00:19:46,439
The Chiefs and I believe
we should follow up the air strikes

310
00:19:46,573 --> 00:19:50,810
with the full version of OPLAN 316

311
00:19:50,910 --> 00:19:51,478
An invasion?

312
00:19:51,578 --> 00:19:52,946
Yes, sir

313
00:19:53,046 --> 00:19:54,681
We can be sure we get all the missiles

314
00:19:54,747 --> 00:19:56,483
and we remove Castro

315
00:19:56,516 --> 00:19:58,184
so this can never happen again

316
00:19:58,284 --> 00:19:59,853
Is this
the Joint Chief's recommendation?

317
00:19:59,919 --> 00:20:01,020
Yes, sir

318
00:20:01,187 --> 00:20:03,490
Our best option
as Bob pointed out this morning

319
00:20:03,590 --> 00:20:07,660
would be to commence the strikes
before the missiles become operational

320
00:20:07,760 --> 00:20:10,797
The invasion happens eight days later

321
00:20:12,665 --> 00:20:14,534
Dean

322
00:20:15,168 --> 00:20:16,769
What do you think?

323
00:20:17,103 --> 00:20:18,137
Gentlemen

324
00:20:18,271 --> 00:20:20,440
for the last fifteen years
I have fought here at this table

325
00:20:20,540 --> 00:20:22,909
alongside your predecessors

326
00:20:22,942 --> 00:20:25,078
in a struggle against the Soviet

327
00:20:25,211 --> 00:20:27,413
I do not wish to seem melodramatic

328
00:20:27,480 --> 00:20:29,449
but I do wish to impress upon you

329
00:20:29,549 --> 00:20:31,618
a lesson I learned with bitter tears

330
00:20:31,718 --> 00:20:33,052
and great sacrifice

331
00:20:33,186 --> 00:20:35,088
The Soviet understands
only one language

332
00:20:35,188 --> 00:20:36,222
action

333
00:20:36,389 --> 00:20:38,024
Respects only one word

334
00:20:38,124 --> 00:20:39,359
Force

335
00:20:39,459 --> 00:20:41,528
I concur with General Taylor

336
00:20:41,661 --> 00:20:44,797
I recommend air strikes
followed by invasion

337
00:20:44,864 --> 00:20:46,466
perhaps

338
00:20:46,599 --> 00:20:48,401
proceeded by an ultimatum
to dismantle the missiles

339
00:20:48,501 --> 00:20:50,036
If that is militarily viable

340
00:20:50,203 --> 00:20:52,539
So it appears we have three options

341
00:20:52,705 --> 00:20:56,910
Number one, a surgical air strike
against the missiles themselves

342
00:20:57,010 --> 00:20:59,212
Two, a much larger air strike
against their air defenses

343
00:20:59,279 --> 00:21:04,350
along with the missiles. And three

344
00:21:04,484 --> 00:21:06,152
invasion

345
00:21:06,252 --> 00:21:09,989
So we're certainly gonna do number one
We're gonna take these missiles out

346
00:21:10,123 --> 00:21:11,457
It seems to me we can't wait very long

347
00:21:11,591 --> 00:21:13,560
We should at leat
be making those preparations

348
00:21:13,660 --> 00:21:14,360
We're preparing to
implement all three options

349
00:21:14,427 --> 00:21:17,997
Though I must stress again, sir
there are risks to the strikes

350
00:21:18,131 --> 00:21:22,202
without the follow-on invasion

351
00:21:22,302 --> 00:21:23,570
You want to be clear, Mr. President

352
00:21:23,703 --> 00:21:26,105
that we've definitely decided
against a political track

353
00:21:28,374 --> 00:21:29,776
Dean

354
00:21:30,910 --> 00:21:34,280
How does this all play out?

355
00:21:34,347 --> 00:21:36,850
Your first step, sir
will be to demand that the Soviet

356
00:21:36,983 --> 00:21:39,719
withdraw the missiles
within 12 to 24 hours

357
00:21:40,320 --> 00:21:41,421
The will refuse

358
00:21:41,554 --> 00:21:43,356
When they do
you will order the strikes

359
00:21:43,423 --> 00:21:44,891
followed by the invasion

360
00:21:45,024 --> 00:21:47,527
They will resist and be overrun

361
00:21:47,594 --> 00:21:51,064
They will retaliate against another
target somewhere else in the world

362
00:21:51,164 --> 00:21:52,432
most likely Berlin

363
00:21:52,932 --> 00:21:55,001
We will honor our treaty commitments

364
00:21:55,068 --> 00:21:56,703
and resist them there

365
00:21:56,803 --> 00:21:59,005
defeating them per our plans

366
00:22:00,507 --> 00:22:03,309
Those plans call for
the use of nuclear weapons

367
00:22:08,448 --> 00:22:10,717
So...

368
00:22:10,817 --> 00:22:12,118
what is the next step?

369
00:22:12,218 --> 00:22:14,087
Hopeful cooler heads will prevail

370
00:22:14,187 --> 00:22:16,022
before we reach the next step

371
00:22:20,493 --> 00:22:21,728
Thank you, gentlemen

372
00:22:35,975 --> 00:22:38,111
What happened in there?

373
00:22:38,244 --> 00:22:39,712
I thought he was going to
give us his decision

374
00:22:39,813 --> 00:22:41,614
Look, I know them. They just need to...

375
00:22:41,681 --> 00:22:43,049
make sure there's no other way
They'll get there

376
00:22:43,116 --> 00:22:45,618
The Kennedys' father
was one of the architects of Munich

377
00:22:45,752 --> 00:22:47,921
There's only one
responsible choice here

378
00:22:48,021 --> 00:22:50,657
So let's hope appeasement
doesn't run in families

379
00:22:50,723 --> 00:22:52,492
I fear weakness does

380
00:23:12,212 --> 00:23:14,848
Jesus Christ

381
00:23:18,218 --> 00:23:21,721
Call me Irish, but I don't
believe in cooler heads prevailing

382
00:23:21,855 --> 00:23:23,056
You know, they think I froze in there

383
00:23:23,189 --> 00:23:24,257
You didn't freeze

384
00:23:24,357 --> 00:23:25,458
You did exactly
what you should have done

385
00:23:25,558 --> 00:23:26,960
you stayed out of the corner

386
00:23:27,093 --> 00:23:28,027
You didn't decide

387
00:23:28,161 --> 00:23:30,396
Acheson's scenario is just...

388
00:23:30,530 --> 00:23:31,431
unacceptable

389
00:23:31,531 --> 00:23:32,765
And he's got more experience
than anyone

390
00:23:32,866 --> 00:23:34,033
There's no expert on the subject

391
00:23:34,133 --> 00:23:37,237
There's no wise old man

392
00:23:37,303 --> 00:23:39,205
Shit, there's just us

393
00:23:39,806 --> 00:23:42,208
Acheson's right

394
00:23:42,275 --> 00:23:44,177
Talk alone is not gonna
accomplish anything

395
00:23:46,079 --> 00:23:47,947
Well, let's bomb the shit out of them

396
00:23:48,414 --> 00:23:49,549
Everybody wants to

397
00:23:49,616 --> 00:23:51,084
Even you

398
00:23:51,217 --> 00:23:52,919
Even me

399
00:23:53,353 --> 00:23:55,188
Right? It sure would feel good

400
00:23:55,688 --> 00:23:56,890
Jack

401
00:23:57,257 --> 00:23:58,358
I'm as conniving as they come

402
00:23:58,458 --> 00:24:01,728
but a sneak attack is just wrong

403
00:24:01,828 --> 00:24:02,996
Things are happening too fast

404
00:24:03,062 --> 00:24:05,398
This is starting to smell like
the Bay of Pigs all over again

405
00:24:05,532 --> 00:24:08,935
Tonight
listening to Taylor and Acheson

406
00:24:09,035 --> 00:24:11,171
I kept seeing Lemnitzer and Dulles

407
00:24:11,237 --> 00:24:12,272
telling me all I had to do was
sign on the dotted line

408
00:24:12,405 --> 00:24:13,373
And that the invasion would succeed

409
00:24:13,540 --> 00:24:16,442
and Castro...

410
00:24:17,110 --> 00:24:18,645
and Castro would be gone

411
00:24:20,413 --> 00:24:21,714
Easy, just like that

412
00:24:27,620 --> 00:24:30,924
There's something...

413
00:24:30,990 --> 00:24:33,259
immoral about
abandoning your own judgment

414
00:24:36,729 --> 00:24:38,631
We just can't let this get out of hand

415
00:24:39,833 --> 00:24:40,934
And we'll do whatever we have to do

416
00:24:41,034 --> 00:24:43,169
to make this come out right

417
00:24:47,240 --> 00:24:48,274
I'm gonna stay here tomorrow

418
00:24:48,374 --> 00:24:49,476
You can't

419
00:24:49,609 --> 00:24:51,945
We talked about this. Your schedule?

420
00:24:51,978 --> 00:24:54,881
Best thing you can do tomorrow
is go to Connecticut

421
00:24:55,515 --> 00:24:56,783
He's right

422
00:24:59,686 --> 00:25:01,387
Yeah

423
00:25:01,488 --> 00:25:02,689
Jesus

424
00:25:17,937 --> 00:25:21,040
Doesn't anybody in Connecticut
have to work today?

425
00:25:21,107 --> 00:25:23,409
We love you, JFK

426
00:25:31,484 --> 00:25:33,653
The shole spectrum of air strikes
is the minumum response

427
00:25:33,720 --> 00:25:34,854
the Joint Chiefs will accept

428
00:25:34,954 --> 00:25:37,390
No, no, no

429
00:25:37,524 --> 00:25:40,026
There is more than one option here

430
00:25:40,126 --> 00:25:41,094
And if one isn't occurring to us

431
00:25:41,227 --> 00:25:42,862
it's because
we haven't thought hard enough

432
00:25:42,929 --> 00:25:45,899
Bobby, sometimes
there is only one right choice

433
00:25:46,032 --> 00:25:47,600
and you thank God when it's so clear

434
00:25:47,734 --> 00:25:49,602
You're talking about a sneak attack

435
00:25:49,669 --> 00:25:51,638
How would that make us look?

436
00:25:51,671 --> 00:25:54,874
A big country blasting a little one
into the stone age

437
00:25:55,008 --> 00:25:56,276
We'll be everyone's favorites

438
00:25:56,342 --> 00:25:59,412
Come on, Bobby. That's naive

439
00:25:59,479 --> 00:26:01,014
You know that better than anybody

440
00:26:01,181 --> 00:26:03,817
And you weren't
so ethically particular

441
00:26:03,917 --> 00:26:06,519
when we were talking about
options for moving Castro at CIA

442
00:26:18,131 --> 00:26:20,066
Bob

443
00:26:20,099 --> 00:26:22,802
If we go ahead with these air strikes

444
00:26:22,902 --> 00:26:26,105
you know what it'll come to in the end

445
00:26:26,172 --> 00:26:28,174
There has got to be something else

446
00:26:28,241 --> 00:26:29,342
Give it to me

447
00:26:29,476 --> 00:26:34,547
I don't care how crazy, inadequate
or stupid it sounds

448
00:26:34,714 --> 00:26:36,583
Give it to me

449
00:26:37,317 --> 00:26:39,619
Six months ago
we gamed out a scenario

450
00:26:39,752 --> 00:26:41,287
It's slow
It doesn't get rid of the missiles

451
00:26:41,421 --> 00:26:43,723
It's got a lot of drawbacks

452
00:26:47,760 --> 00:26:50,330
The scenario
calls for a blockade of Cuba

453
00:27:21,094 --> 00:27:22,962
The situation is worse than we thought

454
00:27:23,029 --> 00:27:25,632
We now count 40 missiles

455
00:27:25,665 --> 00:27:27,767
40 missiles

456
00:27:27,867 --> 00:27:29,002
Longer range IRBM's

457
00:27:29,068 --> 00:27:34,107
They can hit every place
in the country, except Seattle

458
00:27:34,240 --> 00:27:35,942
Mr. President

459
00:27:36,042 --> 00:27:37,710
you give me the order right now

460
00:27:37,844 --> 00:27:41,681
my planes will be ready
to strike in 3 days time

461
00:27:41,815 --> 00:27:43,183
Just say "go"

462
00:27:43,283 --> 00:27:45,652
and my boys
will get those red bastards

463
00:27:47,887 --> 00:27:50,790
General, how long
until the Army's ready?

464
00:27:50,857 --> 00:27:51,858
We've just begun the mobilization

465
00:27:51,958 --> 00:27:54,093
under cover of
a pre-arranged exercise, sir

466
00:27:54,194 --> 00:27:56,162
We're looking at
another week and a half

467
00:27:56,329 --> 00:27:58,832
But you can order the strikes now

468
00:27:59,466 --> 00:28:02,202
The plans call for
an eight day air campaign

469
00:28:02,268 --> 00:28:05,405
It'll light a fire
under the army's ass to get in place

470
00:28:06,339 --> 00:28:08,975
General Lemay, do you truly believe
that's our best course of action?

471
00:28:09,108 --> 00:28:09,676
Mr. President

472
00:28:09,776 --> 00:28:11,878
I believe
it is the only course of action

473
00:28:12,011 --> 00:28:13,913
America is in danger

474
00:28:14,080 --> 00:28:16,115
Those missiles are a threat
to our bomber bases

475
00:28:16,282 --> 00:28:18,184
and the safety of
our nuclear deterrent

476
00:28:18,351 --> 00:28:19,419
Without our deterrent

477
00:28:19,452 --> 00:28:24,157
there's nothing to keep the enemy
from choosing general nuclear war

478
00:28:24,257 --> 00:28:25,458
It's out duty

479
00:28:25,525 --> 00:28:29,062
Our responsibility to the American
people to take out those missiles

480
00:28:29,129 --> 00:28:32,031
and return stability
to the strategic situation

481
00:28:32,165 --> 00:28:34,567
The Big Red Dog
is digging in our back yard

482
00:28:34,701 --> 00:28:36,402
and we are justified in shooting him

483
00:28:36,469 --> 00:28:37,670
Sir

484
00:28:37,770 --> 00:28:41,007
we have a rapidly
closing window of opportunity

485
00:28:41,174 --> 00:28:44,410
where we can to prevent those missiles
from becoming operational

486
00:28:44,544 --> 00:28:46,446
The other options

487
00:28:46,513 --> 00:28:50,316
do not guarantee the end result
that we can guarantee

488
00:28:50,450 --> 00:28:53,086
However, as more time goes by

489
00:28:53,186 --> 00:28:56,256
the less reliable the choice
we can offer you becomes

490
00:28:56,322 --> 00:28:57,190
Mr. President

491
00:28:57,323 --> 00:28:59,526
the motto I chose for SAC

492
00:28:59,626 --> 00:29:01,528
is "Peace is our Profession"

493
00:29:01,594 --> 00:29:04,430
God forbid we find ourselves
in a nuclear exchange

494
00:29:04,464 --> 00:29:06,766
But launched

495
00:29:06,833 --> 00:29:09,002
missiles from Cuba
would kill a lot of Americans

496
00:29:09,102 --> 00:29:10,603
The very presence of those missiles

497
00:29:10,670 --> 00:29:13,072
gives the Soviets
first- strike capability

498
00:29:13,139 --> 00:29:16,409
Those missiles
make a nuclear exchange more likely

499
00:29:16,509 --> 00:29:19,879
And that is why
I'm being such a pain in the ass

500
00:29:20,013 --> 00:29:23,216
abut destroying them
and destroying them immediately

501
00:29:23,316 --> 00:29:25,018
Hell, even Mac agrees

502
00:29:27,086 --> 00:29:28,254
And sir

503
00:29:28,388 --> 00:29:30,924
given your own statements about Cuba

504
00:29:30,990 --> 00:29:35,528
I think a blockade
or a bunch of political talk

505
00:29:35,595 --> 00:29:38,231
would be considered
by a lot of our friends and neutrals

506
00:29:38,364 --> 00:29:40,800
as a pretty weak response

507
00:29:40,934 --> 00:29:46,072
And I suspect many of our own citizens
feel the same way

508
00:29:46,606 --> 00:29:51,544
You're in a pretty bad fix
Mr. President

509
00:29:52,745 --> 00:29:54,848
What did you say?

510
00:29:55,949 --> 00:29:57,984
You're in a pretty bad fix

511
00:29:59,619 --> 00:30:02,956
Maybe you hadn't noticed
you're in it with me

512
00:30:05,592 --> 00:30:06,526
General

513
00:30:06,593 --> 00:30:09,796
what are the Soviets gonna do
when we attack?

514
00:30:10,997 --> 00:30:12,232
Nothing

515
00:30:12,866 --> 00:30:13,800
Nothing?

516
00:30:13,900 --> 00:30:15,368
Nothing

517
00:30:15,435 --> 00:30:18,805
Because the only alternative
open to them

518
00:30:18,905 --> 00:30:21,841
is one they can't choose

519
00:30:22,342 --> 00:30:23,843
You know, they're...

520
00:30:24,010 --> 00:30:26,713
they're not just missiles
we're gonna be destroying, General

521
00:30:26,779 --> 00:30:31,351
If we kill Soviet soldiers
they're gonna respond

522
00:30:31,718 --> 00:30:33,486
How would we respond
if they killed ours?

523
00:30:33,620 --> 00:30:34,854
They're gonna do something, General

524
00:30:34,954 --> 00:30:37,457
I can promise you that

525
00:30:40,994 --> 00:30:42,328
Those goddamn Kennedys
are gonna destroy this country

526
00:30:42,462 --> 00:30:45,331
if we don't do something about this

527
00:30:46,900 --> 00:30:50,203
We're headed out to the back yard
to look for that Big Red Dog

528
00:30:51,137 --> 00:30:52,272
Thanks, Bob

529
00:30:52,772 --> 00:30:55,108
I was hoping Lemay pushed you

530
00:30:55,241 --> 00:30:57,610
'Cause I was ready to knock
that son-of-a-bitch across the room

531
00:30:57,710 --> 00:30:58,545
We knew it was coming
And I'll tell you one thing, Kenny

532
00:30:58,645 --> 00:31:00,513
Those brass hats
have one big advantage

533
00:31:00,580 --> 00:31:01,981
That is that
if we do what they want us to do

534
00:31:02,115 --> 00:31:04,150
none of us will be left alive
to tell them they were wrong

535
00:31:04,951 --> 00:31:05,685
Mr. President

536
00:31:05,785 --> 00:31:07,720
we need to go over
what you're going to say

537
00:31:08,254 --> 00:31:09,989
Gromyko should be on his way by now

538
00:31:10,123 --> 00:31:12,525
There's still no sign they know that
we know about the missiles

539
00:31:12,625 --> 00:31:13,927
We're gonna keep it that way

540
00:31:29,809 --> 00:31:31,511
Kenny

541
00:31:31,578 --> 00:31:33,880
Be right there

542
00:31:33,980 --> 00:31:36,049
I'm getting funny questions
from the guys

543
00:31:36,149 --> 00:31:37,884
Yeah? What sort of questions?

544
00:31:37,984 --> 00:31:40,220
About some sort of
"military exercises"?

545
00:31:40,353 --> 00:31:41,254
You want me to do my job
handling the press

546
00:31:41,387 --> 00:31:43,189
I need to know what's going on

547
00:31:43,289 --> 00:31:44,157
Military exercises?

548
00:31:44,224 --> 00:31:46,726
Yeah. Military exercises

549
00:31:46,826 --> 00:31:48,595
Haven't heard anything about it

550
00:31:48,728 --> 00:31:49,395
Ask Bundy

551
00:31:49,462 --> 00:31:51,431
I did. He said to ask you

552
00:31:53,566 --> 00:31:56,035
Mr. Gromyko! This way, please!

553
00:32:01,374 --> 00:32:02,675
Robert

554
00:32:03,209 --> 00:32:04,377
Hugh, how are you?

555
00:32:08,114 --> 00:32:09,115
Excuse me, Joan

556
00:32:09,983 --> 00:32:12,886
So, tell me about this military
exercise going on in Puerto Rico

557
00:32:12,952 --> 00:32:13,553
What?

558
00:32:13,686 --> 00:32:15,989
It's called... ORTSAC, I believe

559
00:32:16,055 --> 00:32:17,657
Castro spelled backwards

560
00:32:17,757 --> 00:32:19,359
ORTSAC?

561
00:32:19,793 --> 00:32:21,394
I don't know what you're talking about

562
00:32:21,461 --> 00:32:22,395
Me either

563
00:32:22,495 --> 00:32:23,429
Why?

564
00:32:23,530 --> 00:32:25,899
Because maybe the President
and Gromyko are gonna talk about it

565
00:32:25,965 --> 00:32:28,535
You're trying to drum something up
Johnny. Forget it

566
00:32:28,635 --> 00:32:30,603
This meeting's been
on the books for months

567
00:32:31,204 --> 00:32:34,274
Far as I know, it's just a friendly
talk on U. S -Soviet relations

568
00:32:38,311 --> 00:32:40,814
Mr. President!
Will you make a statement, sir?

569
00:32:40,947 --> 00:32:42,382
Alright, hold it, fellas

570
00:32:42,448 --> 00:32:44,951
You'll get your pictures

571
00:32:45,051 --> 00:32:46,085
Does it?

572
00:32:48,822 --> 00:32:50,390
I'll be damned

573
00:32:52,192 --> 00:32:53,960
Kind of simple for the Pentagon

574
00:33:04,103 --> 00:33:06,005
Mr. Gromyko

575
00:33:06,105 --> 00:33:08,107
Hold on one minute

576
00:33:12,946 --> 00:33:14,781
Gentlemen
would you mind shaking hands?

577
00:33:16,483 --> 00:33:19,319
So that there should be
no misunderstanding

578
00:33:19,385 --> 00:33:20,787
the position of the United States

579
00:33:20,854 --> 00:33:21,754
which has been made clear
by the Attorney General

580
00:33:21,921 --> 00:33:23,756
to Ambassador Dobrynin here

581
00:33:23,857 --> 00:33:25,091
I shall read a sentence
from my statement

582
00:33:25,258 --> 00:33:27,527
to the press dated September 13th

583
00:33:28,027 --> 00:33:31,898
"Should missiles or offensive weapon
be placed in Cuba"

584
00:33:31,998 --> 00:33:35,135
"it would present the gravest threat
to U. S. national security"

585
00:33:35,268 --> 00:33:36,836
Mr. President

586
00:33:36,970 --> 00:33:40,440
as Premier Kruschev's own statement
of September 13th assured you

587
00:33:40,540 --> 00:33:42,075
our military assistance to Cuba

588
00:33:42,208 --> 00:33:44,511
is of a defensive nature only

589
00:33:49,849 --> 00:33:51,818
So I did not misunderstand you?

590
00:33:51,918 --> 00:33:55,054
There are no offensive weapons in Cuba

591
00:33:55,188 --> 00:33:57,957
Premier Kruschev's statement
of September 13th

592
00:33:57,991 --> 00:34:00,660
remains the position
of the Soviet government

593
00:34:00,727 --> 00:34:03,163
To that I have nothing to add

594
00:34:04,197 --> 00:34:05,765
Well, that's good enough for me

595
00:34:06,566 --> 00:34:07,700
Thanks so much

596
00:34:07,801 --> 00:34:09,369
Thank you

597
00:34:11,871 --> 00:34:14,541
Gentlemen
if you'll come with me, please

598
00:34:14,607 --> 00:34:16,309
A most instructive meeting

599
00:34:22,315 --> 00:34:23,216
What happened?

600
00:34:23,316 --> 00:34:24,918
Lying bastard

601
00:34:25,018 --> 00:34:26,085
Lied right to my face

602
00:34:26,219 --> 00:34:27,320
We're split down the middle

603
00:34:27,353 --> 00:34:30,256
If I held a vote, I think air strike
would beat blockade by a vote or two

604
00:34:30,323 --> 00:34:33,993
I want a consensus
Either air strike or blockade

605
00:34:34,060 --> 00:34:35,128
Something everyone's gonna stand by

606
00:34:35,261 --> 00:34:37,263
even if they don't like it

607
00:34:37,397 --> 00:34:39,032
And I need it by Saturday

608
00:34:39,065 --> 00:34:40,500
So make it happen

609
00:34:40,600 --> 00:34:42,068
What if I can't?

610
00:34:43,436 --> 00:34:46,272
We go into this split
the Russians will know it

611
00:34:46,406 --> 00:34:47,907
And they'll use it against us

612
00:34:47,974 --> 00:34:50,677
Have you cancelled Chicago
and the rest of the weekend yet?

613
00:34:50,777 --> 00:34:53,613
You don't show for Chicago, everyone
will know there's something going on

614
00:34:53,746 --> 00:34:54,848
I don't care. Just cancel it

615
00:34:55,014 --> 00:34:56,883
Forget it

616
00:34:57,750 --> 00:35:00,453
I'm not calling
and canceling on Daley

617
00:35:02,555 --> 00:35:04,624
You call and cancel on Daley

618
00:35:04,757 --> 00:35:06,025
You're scared to cancel on Daley

619
00:35:06,159 --> 00:35:08,394
You're damn right, I'm scared

620
00:35:10,964 --> 00:35:12,899
Well, I'm not

621
00:35:16,202 --> 00:35:17,737
Watch this

622
00:35:19,205 --> 00:35:21,107
Welcome to Chicago, Mr. President

623
00:35:21,141 --> 00:35:23,176
Mr. Mayor, I wouldn't
miss this event for the world

624
00:35:28,181 --> 00:35:29,282
Let's go

625
00:35:29,883 --> 00:35:32,619
Tonight you're going to
experience true Midwest cunning

626
00:35:33,419 --> 00:35:34,287
What's going on?
Now the guys are hounding me

627
00:35:34,420 --> 00:35:36,723
about some sort of troop movements
in Florida

628
00:35:36,790 --> 00:35:37,724
What are you telling them?

629
00:35:37,791 --> 00:35:38,758
The truth. I don't know

630
00:35:38,892 --> 00:35:39,926
Am I out of the loop on something?

631
00:35:40,026 --> 00:35:41,828
No

632
00:35:41,895 --> 00:35:45,398
Tell 'em you've looked into it
and all it is an exercise

633
00:35:46,599 --> 00:35:49,602
And Pierre, tomorrow
the President may have a cold

634
00:35:49,769 --> 00:35:50,503
A what?

635
00:35:50,603 --> 00:35:52,105
A cold

636
00:35:54,274 --> 00:35:56,376
Do I get any input around here?

637
00:35:58,211 --> 00:35:59,546
Yeah

638
00:35:59,646 --> 00:36:01,714
How bad it is, is up to you

639
00:36:09,722 --> 00:36:11,891
There are major rail disruptions
in the south

640
00:36:12,025 --> 00:36:13,993
two airbome divisions are on alert

641
00:36:14,227 --> 00:36:17,330
Sounds to me like that
exercise is an invasion

642
00:36:17,497 --> 00:36:19,866
You know how Bobby has it in
for the state of Mississippi

643
00:36:19,899 --> 00:36:21,401
We're invading Cuba

644
00:36:22,469 --> 00:36:24,804
Dammit, we are not invading Cuba!

645
00:36:24,871 --> 00:36:26,272
Are you crazy?

646
00:36:26,406 --> 00:36:28,475
Nobody gives a rat's ass about Cuba!

647
00:36:28,608 --> 00:36:30,076
Not now, not ever!

648
00:36:30,210 --> 00:36:33,012
If you print that, all you're
gonna do is inflame the situation

649
00:36:33,112 --> 00:36:34,714
And nobody talks to assholes
who inflame situations

650
00:36:34,781 --> 00:36:36,749
Assholes like that

651
00:36:36,850 --> 00:36:41,087
can find themselves cut
out of the loop

652
00:36:41,187 --> 00:36:43,590
That's the first time
you've ever threatened me

653
00:36:46,092 --> 00:36:47,160
All right

654
00:36:47,260 --> 00:36:49,362
I won't print anything
until I have another source

655
00:36:49,429 --> 00:36:50,797
But I promise you I'll get one

656
00:36:56,136 --> 00:36:57,003
Bobby?

657
00:36:57,070 --> 00:36:58,838
We've got a consensus for a blockade

658
00:36:58,938 --> 00:37:00,673
but it won't last past tomorrow

659
00:37:00,773 --> 00:37:02,475
You have to bring him back

660
00:37:02,575 --> 00:37:03,309
By the way

661
00:37:03,443 --> 00:37:04,911
China invaded India today

662
00:37:05,044 --> 00:37:05,912
You're kidding, aren't you?

663
00:37:06,012 --> 00:37:07,547
I wish I were

664
00:37:07,647 --> 00:37:10,650
Galbraith's handling it in New Delhi

665
00:37:10,750 --> 00:37:12,585
Makes you wonder what's coming next

666
00:37:12,652 --> 00:37:16,656
What is it about the free world that
pisses the rest of the world off?

667
00:37:16,723 --> 00:37:18,958
I don't know
We have Tupperware parties?

668
00:37:19,726 --> 00:37:20,994
Maybe

669
00:37:21,461 --> 00:37:22,295
I'll see you tomorrow

670
00:37:22,362 --> 00:37:23,329
Okay

671
00:37:23,396 --> 00:37:25,031
The President has a cold

672
00:37:25,098 --> 00:37:27,367
He's canceling
the remainder of this trip

673
00:37:27,467 --> 00:37:29,502
and returning to Washington
on the advice of his doctor

674
00:37:29,602 --> 00:37:31,571
Is that the final word?

675
00:37:35,975 --> 00:37:39,145
President Kennedy!
How do you feel, Mr. President?

676
00:37:48,588 --> 00:37:52,091
Mr. President, our deliberations
have led us to the conclusion

677
00:37:52,158 --> 00:37:56,463
that a blockade of offensive weapons
to Cuba is our best option

678
00:37:56,563 --> 00:37:59,799
A strong showing of support from
the Organization of American States

679
00:37:59,866 --> 00:38:01,401
would give us
an umbrella of legitimacy

680
00:38:01,534 --> 00:38:03,603
A blockade
is technically an act of war

681
00:38:03,670 --> 00:38:06,506
Therefore we recommend
calling the action a quarantine

682
00:38:06,606 --> 00:38:10,443
Let's hope that translates
into Russian the way we want it to

683
00:38:11,478 --> 00:38:13,947
There are between 20...

684
00:38:14,047 --> 00:38:16,282
and 30 Soviet ships
underway to cuba at this time

685
00:38:16,783 --> 00:38:18,284
800 miles out

686
00:38:18,351 --> 00:38:19,853
the navy will stop them

687
00:38:19,986 --> 00:38:20,854
board

688
00:38:20,920 --> 00:38:22,956
and any vessels containing weapons
will be turned back

689
00:38:23,123 --> 00:38:25,892
A quarantine prevents
any more missiles from reaching Cuba

690
00:38:26,025 --> 00:38:28,161
but it doesn't remove
the missiles already there

691
00:38:28,261 --> 00:38:31,898
It gives the Soviets a chance
to pull back without a war

692
00:38:31,931 --> 00:38:33,600
If they refuse to remove the missiles

693
00:38:33,733 --> 00:38:36,636
we retain the option
to strike and invade

694
00:38:36,769 --> 00:38:40,440
A sneak attack is counter to
what the United States stands for

695
00:38:40,540 --> 00:38:42,842
It leaves us no room for maneuver

696
00:38:42,942 --> 00:38:45,812
And the inevitable Soviet response
would force us into a war

697
00:38:45,979 --> 00:38:47,914
Mr. President
there are still those of us

698
00:38:47,981 --> 00:38:50,683
who believe
we should proceed with the strikes

699
00:38:50,850 --> 00:38:54,187
With the blockade
we lose strategic surprise

700
00:38:54,254 --> 00:38:56,856
and we also run the risk of the Soviets
launching the first strike against us

701
00:38:56,923 --> 00:38:59,058
if they decide they have to
use the missiles or lose them

702
00:39:01,961 --> 00:39:03,797
So quarantine...

703
00:39:03,930 --> 00:39:05,598
or air strike

704
00:39:05,698 --> 00:39:08,201
There is a third option

705
00:39:08,701 --> 00:39:13,740
With either course we undertake
the risk of nuclear war

706
00:39:13,873 --> 00:39:18,478
So maybe one of us in this room
should be a coward

707
00:39:19,078 --> 00:39:21,648
So I guess I'll be

708
00:39:21,714 --> 00:39:24,451
A third course is to strike a deal

709
00:39:24,884 --> 00:39:27,754
We trade Guantanamo
and our missiles in Turkey

710
00:39:27,821 --> 00:39:29,522
get them to pull their missiles out

711
00:39:29,656 --> 00:39:31,558
We employ a back channel

712
00:39:31,591 --> 00:39:34,727
We attribute the idea to U. N. Thant

713
00:39:34,828 --> 00:39:37,964
U Thant then raises it at the U. N.

714
00:39:39,732 --> 00:39:42,202
I don't think that's possible, Adlai

715
00:39:45,338 --> 00:39:47,307
I've not yet made my final decision

716
00:39:47,440 --> 00:39:50,210
I'll be asking the networks
for airtime on Monday night

717
00:39:50,276 --> 00:39:52,545
We'll announce
our course of action then

718
00:39:54,180 --> 00:39:57,117
Ted, get to work on speeches
for both quarantine

719
00:39:57,183 --> 00:39:58,785
and air strike

720
00:40:00,320 --> 00:40:02,255
Thank you for all your advice
gentlemen

721
00:40:03,823 --> 00:40:05,658
Did you hear Adlai?

722
00:40:05,725 --> 00:40:08,428
You'd think nobody
learned anything from World War Two

723
00:40:08,528 --> 00:40:09,762
Somebody had to say it

724
00:40:09,863 --> 00:40:12,532
I respect Adlai for having the guts
to risk looking like an appeaser

725
00:40:12,632 --> 00:40:13,933
We have to pull him

726
00:40:14,033 --> 00:40:17,237
He won't be able to handle
the Soviets in front of the U. N.

727
00:40:17,370 --> 00:40:18,071
Zorin will eat him alive

728
00:40:18,138 --> 00:40:19,706
We've got bigger problems right now

729
00:40:20,907 --> 00:40:22,108
Ladies?

730
00:40:22,208 --> 00:40:23,376
No, thank you

731
00:40:27,514 --> 00:40:29,382
Honey, I'll be right back

732
00:40:37,257 --> 00:40:38,458
Adlai

733
00:40:40,960 --> 00:40:43,563
Just can't seem to
get away from you guys

734
00:40:43,663 --> 00:40:45,799
Escaping from a night on the town?

735
00:40:45,865 --> 00:40:47,734
As D. C. 's most popular playboy

736
00:40:47,834 --> 00:40:50,637
the President felt my presence
would be sorely missed, so...

737
00:40:50,770 --> 00:40:53,773
in the interest of National Security

738
00:40:53,807 --> 00:40:55,275
here I am

739
00:40:55,375 --> 00:40:57,544
Yes. Gotta keep up appearances

740
00:40:57,644 --> 00:40:59,879
Of course, I don't any more

741
00:41:01,347 --> 00:41:03,216
I'm a political dead man

742
00:41:03,616 --> 00:41:07,454
Did you ever see anyone
cut his own throat like I did today?

743
00:41:08,688 --> 00:41:10,690
No

744
00:41:10,790 --> 00:41:12,325
It's alright

745
00:41:12,425 --> 00:41:13,359
By the way

746
00:41:13,493 --> 00:41:15,361
I spoke to a friend

747
00:41:15,428 --> 00:41:17,597
Reston and Frankel have the story

748
00:41:17,664 --> 00:41:20,066
The Times is going to run it tomorrow

749
00:41:22,769 --> 00:41:24,404
We're not gonna make it to Monday

750
00:41:24,537 --> 00:41:25,338
Shit

751
00:41:25,472 --> 00:41:27,373
I'll get Sorenson
to try to lean on Reston

752
00:41:27,540 --> 00:41:29,676
But you're gonna
have to call Orville Dryfoos

753
00:41:29,809 --> 00:41:32,412
This is the sort of decision
a publisher makes himself

754
00:41:32,846 --> 00:41:34,214
Alright

755
00:41:34,280 --> 00:41:36,116
Thanks, Kenny

756
00:41:37,117 --> 00:41:38,184
Yes sir, I understand

757
00:41:38,284 --> 00:41:40,320
But we held on the Bay of Pigs

758
00:41:40,420 --> 00:41:41,788
and it was the
biggest mistake of my life

759
00:41:41,855 --> 00:41:42,622
What makes this different?

760
00:41:42,722 --> 00:41:43,723
Orville, I'm asking you
to hold the story

761
00:41:43,890 --> 00:41:47,293
until I can present
our course of action on Monday night

762
00:41:49,729 --> 00:41:50,330
Alright

763
00:41:50,463 --> 00:41:52,365
But I'm gonna need a reason
to give my boys

764
00:41:52,499 --> 00:41:53,833
They're gonna be screaming
for my head on a plate

765
00:41:53,967 --> 00:41:56,436
Orville, you tell them this

766
00:41:56,503 --> 00:41:58,438
That they'll be saving lives

767
00:41:58,605 --> 00:42:00,440
including their own

768
00:42:02,408 --> 00:42:04,043
Yes, Mr. President

769
00:42:30,737 --> 00:42:32,772
How many Congressmen
have not responded yet?

770
00:42:32,872 --> 00:42:34,207
Fourteen

771
00:42:34,641 --> 00:42:36,543
Boggs is in the Gulf fishing?

772
00:42:36,609 --> 00:42:38,678
I thought
he was supposed to be campaigning

773
00:42:38,745 --> 00:42:39,846
He's not gone for long, sir

774
00:42:39,913 --> 00:42:42,949
Jesus. Get a plane out there
and get him back

775
00:42:44,484 --> 00:42:46,286
He wants to talk to LeMay again

776
00:42:46,653 --> 00:42:48,021
He's still considering air strikes

777
00:42:57,897 --> 00:42:59,566
None of this works tomorrow

778
00:42:59,632 --> 00:43:00,834
Figure out how to cancel it

779
00:43:00,900 --> 00:43:02,135
Yes, sir

780
00:43:03,937 --> 00:43:05,905
We're on the phones

781
00:43:15,081 --> 00:43:17,784
Cam, can you guarantee me
you'll get all the missiles?

782
00:43:21,387 --> 00:43:23,823
Sir, I guarantee we'll get
all the missiles we know about

783
00:43:23,923 --> 00:43:24,858
Mr. President

784
00:43:24,991 --> 00:43:27,293
we can get better than
90 percent of them

785
00:43:31,498 --> 00:43:34,601
I'll brief the Congressional
leadership tomorrow evening at five

786
00:43:36,069 --> 00:43:39,372
At seven o'clock, all United States
armed forces worldwide

787
00:43:39,506 --> 00:43:41,341
will stand up to DEFCON 3

788
00:43:42,475 --> 00:43:44,711
I have a brief statement

789
00:43:44,811 --> 00:43:46,880
President Kennedy
will address the nation tonight

790
00:43:47,013 --> 00:43:48,515
On radio and television

791
00:43:48,648 --> 00:43:51,684
on a subject of
the hightest national urgency

792
00:43:51,751 --> 00:43:54,687
He has requested airtime
on all three networks for seven p. m.

793
00:43:54,821 --> 00:43:55,855
Thank you very much

794
00:44:25,718 --> 00:44:26,953
Mr. President

795
00:44:27,120 --> 00:44:32,025
Congress cannot give you
the support you're looking for

796
00:44:32,158 --> 00:44:32,759
Mr. President?

797
00:44:32,859 --> 00:44:33,893
Sir?

798
00:44:33,993 --> 00:44:36,429
If they want this goddamn job
they can have it

799
00:44:36,529 --> 00:44:37,897
It's no great joy to me

800
00:44:37,964 --> 00:44:39,999
Mr. President, here's the speech
with those changes you wanted

801
00:44:40,133 --> 00:44:40,800
I need a minute

802
00:44:40,900 --> 00:44:41,968
Kenny, no

803
00:44:42,068 --> 00:44:43,837
A minute

804
00:44:48,808 --> 00:44:50,443
I don't want a goddamn pep talk

805
00:44:50,577 --> 00:44:52,345
You're not the Harvard
quarterback anymore

806
00:44:52,879 --> 00:44:54,414
We're on the brink here

807
00:44:54,481 --> 00:44:56,883
They're trying to second-guess me
into World War Three

808
00:44:56,983 --> 00:44:57,884
Well, it's not gonna happen

809
00:44:57,951 --> 00:44:59,085
What did you think
Congress was gonna do?

810
00:44:59,219 --> 00:45:02,255
Offer you unconditional support?

811
00:45:02,355 --> 00:45:04,424
Kiss your Catholic ass?

812
00:45:04,858 --> 00:45:06,493
They don't think
we even deserve to be here

813
00:45:06,826 --> 00:45:08,228
What the hell do you think?

814
00:45:08,695 --> 00:45:10,430
I think we haven't been
that impressive to date

815
00:45:10,563 --> 00:45:12,632
and they have good reason
to question our judgment

816
00:45:13,099 --> 00:45:14,934
What do you want, Kenny?

817
00:45:15,802 --> 00:45:16,469
I want you to sit down

818
00:45:16,569 --> 00:45:18,071
I'm not gonna sit down

819
00:45:19,072 --> 00:45:20,440
I want you to sit down

820
00:45:20,540 --> 00:45:21,875
loosen your tie
and take a minute for yourself

821
00:45:21,941 --> 00:45:22,909
I haven't got a minute!

822
00:45:23,009 --> 00:45:25,912
You're the President
of the United States

823
00:45:26,012 --> 00:45:28,481
They can wait for you

824
00:45:33,253 --> 00:45:34,921
Why not

825
00:45:37,957 --> 00:45:39,359
Things can't get much worse

826
00:45:39,459 --> 00:45:41,628
We could have to...

827
00:45:41,761 --> 00:45:44,931
go down to Lyndon's ranch again
dressed up as cowboys

828
00:45:47,333 --> 00:45:50,170
Shoot deer
out of the back of his convertible

829
00:45:52,272 --> 00:45:54,207
That was a bad day

830
00:45:57,477 --> 00:46:02,081
You know
I thought there'd be ore good days

831
00:46:04,417 --> 00:46:06,619
You know
back when we were in the wards

832
00:46:07,353 --> 00:46:09,689
the day Bobby
made me come down to meet you

833
00:46:10,824 --> 00:46:12,659
I didn't get you at first

834
00:46:13,726 --> 00:46:15,161
I thought you were lucky

835
00:46:16,262 --> 00:46:17,630
Your father had a lot of money

836
00:46:18,498 --> 00:46:19,699
You were skinny

837
00:46:20,266 --> 00:46:22,135
Girls loved you

838
00:46:22,869 --> 00:46:25,805
I thought I could
beat you and Bobby up together

839
00:46:26,706 --> 00:46:28,007
But he...

840
00:46:28,575 --> 00:46:32,545
just kept going on and on about you

841
00:46:33,079 --> 00:46:35,482
I thought it was
because he was your brother

842
00:46:38,718 --> 00:46:40,820
But I was wrong

843
00:46:43,456 --> 00:46:44,991
I was wrong

844
00:47:02,709 --> 00:47:04,511
You sleeping?

845
00:47:05,345 --> 00:47:07,380
No, not much

846
00:47:08,014 --> 00:47:10,483
I slept last night, though

847
00:47:10,550 --> 00:47:15,155
And when I woke up

848
00:47:15,221 --> 00:47:19,259
I'd forgotten that
all this had happened

849
00:47:19,993 --> 00:47:21,928
And then I remembered

850
00:47:22,061 --> 00:47:27,200
and I just wished for
a second somebody else was President

851
00:47:28,234 --> 00:47:29,869
You mean that?

852
00:47:31,471 --> 00:47:33,506
I said for a second

853
00:47:39,512 --> 00:47:43,283
Boy, there is
a lot of noise out there, Kenny

854
00:47:47,520 --> 00:47:49,756
You know what you're doing
Mr. President

855
00:47:51,324 --> 00:47:53,460
You're gonna make
the best call you can

856
00:47:53,526 --> 00:47:54,961
And you know
they're gonna second-guess you

857
00:47:55,028 --> 00:47:56,563
So what?

858
00:47:58,131 --> 00:48:00,733
We're just gonna have to
take our beatings as we go

859
00:48:06,406 --> 00:48:08,074
So what are we gonna do now?

860
00:48:10,009 --> 00:48:11,344
I'm going on TV

861
00:48:20,620 --> 00:48:22,922
Maybe the American people
will go with me

862
00:48:24,457 --> 00:48:26,292
Even if their...

863
00:48:27,494 --> 00:48:30,029
elected representatives won't

864
00:48:35,568 --> 00:48:37,971
You wear something nice for the TV

865
00:48:38,037 --> 00:48:39,572
Make sure Jackie picks it

866
00:48:45,779 --> 00:48:47,914
Excuse me

867
00:48:51,818 --> 00:48:53,820
Okay, everybody. I think we're ready

868
00:48:57,123 --> 00:48:58,558
No. I'm fine

869
00:48:59,993 --> 00:49:01,461
Mr. President, in five...

870
00:49:01,561 --> 00:49:04,831
four... three... two...

871
00:49:04,931 --> 00:49:06,966
Good evening, my fellow citizens

872
00:49:07,000 --> 00:49:09,102
This government, as promised

873
00:49:09,235 --> 00:49:11,271
has maintained
the closest surveillance

874
00:49:11,404 --> 00:49:14,741
of the Soviet military build-up
on the island of Cuba

875
00:49:14,808 --> 00:49:16,376
Within the past week

876
00:49:16,443 --> 00:49:18,044
unmistakable evidence
has established the fact

877
00:49:18,144 --> 00:49:22,215
that a series of
offensive missile sites

878
00:49:22,282 --> 00:49:25,318
is now in preparation
on that imprisoned island

879
00:49:25,418 --> 00:49:27,554
The purpose of these bases
can be none other than to provide

880
00:49:27,620 --> 00:49:29,222
a nuclear strike capability

881
00:49:29,289 --> 00:49:32,592
against the Western Hemisphere

882
00:49:32,659 --> 00:49:35,295
Acting therefore
in the defense of our own security

883
00:49:35,328 --> 00:49:38,031
and under the authority entrusted
to me by the Constitution

884
00:49:38,164 --> 00:49:42,202
I have directed that the following
initial steps be taken immediately

885
00:49:42,235 --> 00:49:43,103
First

886
00:49:43,203 --> 00:49:45,205
to halt this offensive build-up

887
00:49:45,338 --> 00:49:47,740
a strict quarantine on
all offensive military equipment

888
00:49:47,907 --> 00:49:50,110
under shipment to Cuba
is being initiated

889
00:49:50,176 --> 00:49:52,912
All ships of any kind bound for Cuba

890
00:49:52,979 --> 00:49:54,948
form whatever nation or port

891
00:49:55,014 --> 00:49:58,785
will, if found to contain cargoes
of offensive weapons, be turned back

892
00:49:58,818 --> 00:49:59,652
Second

893
00:49:59,719 --> 00:50:02,522
I have directed
the continued and increased

894
00:50:02,655 --> 00:50:04,457
close surveillance of Cuba
and its military build-up

895
00:50:04,591 --> 00:50:06,860
Should these military
preparations continue

896
00:50:06,993 --> 00:50:09,062
further action will be justified

897
00:50:09,229 --> 00:50:12,766
I have directed the Armed Forces
to prepare for any eventualities

898
00:50:12,866 --> 00:50:13,900
And third

899
00:50:14,067 --> 00:50:16,236
It shall be the policy of this nation

900
00:50:16,336 --> 00:50:18,671
to regard any nuclear missile
launched from Cuba

901
00:50:18,738 --> 00:50:23,176
against any nation in the
Western Hemisphere as an attack

902
00:50:23,309 --> 00:50:25,078
by the Soviet Union
on the United States

903
00:50:25,211 --> 00:50:28,615
requiring a full retaliatory response
upon the Soviet Union

904
00:50:37,590 --> 00:50:38,992
Good speech, Teddy

905
00:50:39,526 --> 00:50:41,961
I guess I get to keep my job

906
00:50:44,264 --> 00:50:45,432
No

907
00:50:45,532 --> 00:50:47,634
It was a really good speech

908
00:50:47,734 --> 00:50:50,603
I can't imagine what you did
with the air strikes version

909
00:50:54,607 --> 00:50:56,075
I wasn't able to write, Kenny

910
00:50:58,711 --> 00:51:01,881
It's kind of hard
to write the unthinkable

911
00:51:01,981 --> 00:51:05,552
I tried, I just...

912
00:51:07,454 --> 00:51:10,790
I couldn't

913
00:51:12,892 --> 00:51:14,794
We're getting the Soviet response

914
00:51:14,894 --> 00:51:16,563
It's coming in on the teletype

915
00:51:18,064 --> 00:51:19,499
"The community of nations recognizes"

916
00:51:19,599 --> 00:51:22,001
"the fundamental right
of freedom of the seas... "

917
00:51:22,035 --> 00:51:23,570
THis is horseshit

918
00:51:24,270 --> 00:51:25,371
I agree

919
00:51:32,112 --> 00:51:34,647
They don't know how to respond yet

920
00:51:35,648 --> 00:51:37,951
So now you're Kruschev

921
00:51:38,017 --> 00:51:39,552
What do you do?

922
00:51:43,890 --> 00:51:46,559
You run the blockade

923
00:51:46,626 --> 00:51:47,660
They'll run the blockade

924
00:51:47,727 --> 00:51:51,397
Which is what they appear to
be preparing to do, Mr. President

925
00:51:51,431 --> 00:51:54,167
We're tracking 26 ships
inbound for Cuba

926
00:51:54,234 --> 00:51:56,603
They show no sign of changing course

927
00:51:56,703 --> 00:51:59,139
The closest ships
the Gagarin and the Kimovsk

928
00:51:59,205 --> 00:52:01,775
will make the quarantine line
by this time tomorrow

929
00:52:01,875 --> 00:52:04,711
Admiral Anderson
if the ships do not stop

930
00:52:04,811 --> 00:52:07,580
exactly what are
our rules of engagement?

931
00:52:07,580 --> 00:52:10,884
Russian- speaking personnel
have been transferred to our ships

932
00:52:10,950 --> 00:52:12,886
When the quarantine
takes place in the morning

933
00:52:12,886 --> 00:52:16,389
our ships will attempt radio contact
with approaching vessels

934
00:52:16,556 --> 00:52:20,193
They'll be ordered to reduce speed
and stand by for inspection

935
00:52:20,260 --> 00:52:23,263
An inspection team will then
board and search the vessel

936
00:52:23,329 --> 00:52:26,566
If weapons are found, the ship will be
ordered out of the quarantine area

937
00:52:26,666 --> 00:52:27,801
If they refuse

938
00:52:27,967 --> 00:52:29,669
they'll be towed into the nearest port

939
00:52:29,769 --> 00:52:33,206
What if the ship doesn't stop
for inspection or want to be towed?

940
00:52:33,273 --> 00:52:35,241
We fire a warning shot
across their bow

941
00:52:35,341 --> 00:52:37,944
And what happens
if the ship ignores the warning shot?

942
00:52:38,044 --> 00:52:40,146
Wen then fire at its rudder

943
00:52:40,280 --> 00:52:41,648
disable it
and carry on our inspection

944
00:52:41,781 --> 00:52:45,151
There will be no shooting
without my explicit orders

945
00:52:45,185 --> 00:52:46,786
Is that understood?

946
00:52:46,886 --> 00:52:48,221
Yes sir

947
00:52:48,321 --> 00:52:50,156
Well, Admiral
looks like it's up to the navy

948
00:52:50,223 --> 00:52:52,025
The navy won't let you down, sir

949
00:52:52,058 --> 00:52:53,760
There is one other thing
Mr. President

950
00:52:53,827 --> 00:52:57,130
We're commencing low-level photography
runs over Cuba this morning

951
00:52:57,263 --> 00:52:59,899
It'll be more detailed
than the U-2 photography

952
00:53:00,033 --> 00:53:03,169
We'll firm up our estimates
of the missiles' readiness

953
00:53:03,269 --> 00:53:06,739
and develop target packages for strikes
if you should order them, sir

954
00:53:06,806 --> 00:53:07,574
To protect our pilots

955
00:53:07,640 --> 00:53:10,143
we're prepared to retaliate
against any SAM site

956
00:53:10,310 --> 00:53:12,545
or anti-aircraft battery
that may open fire

957
00:53:12,579 --> 00:53:14,114
We have a flight of Thunderchiefs
that'll be able to

958
00:53:14,180 --> 00:53:17,717
respond within minutes
to any attacks on our planes

959
00:53:25,458 --> 00:53:26,693
I've got a bad feeling about
what's going on in there

960
00:53:26,826 --> 00:53:28,261
In the morning

961
00:53:28,394 --> 00:53:30,330
I'm taking charge of the blockade
from the situation room

962
00:53:30,463 --> 00:53:32,899
And McNamara is gonna set up shop
in the flag plot at the Pentagon

963
00:53:32,999 --> 00:53:33,433
He'll keep an eye on things there

964
00:53:33,533 --> 00:53:34,234
Good

965
00:53:34,300 --> 00:53:36,569
You get armed boarders
climbing on the Soviet ships

966
00:53:36,636 --> 00:53:38,371
with shots being fired across bows

967
00:53:38,471 --> 00:53:39,906
What about these low-level flights?

968
00:53:39,973 --> 00:53:40,573
We need the flights

969
00:53:40,707 --> 00:53:41,374
They're starting in what?

970
00:53:41,441 --> 00:53:43,076
An hour

971
00:53:43,143 --> 00:53:44,711
Do you realize what you're in for?

972
00:53:44,778 --> 00:53:46,279
We need the flights

973
00:53:46,412 --> 00:53:47,680
because the minute that
first missile becomes operational

974
00:53:47,781 --> 00:53:48,748
we gotta go in there and destroy them

975
00:53:48,815 --> 00:53:50,750
Fair enough. But Castro's on alert

976
00:53:50,850 --> 00:53:54,554
and we're flying attack planes
over their sites on the deck

977
00:53:55,054 --> 00:53:58,525
There's no way for them to know
we're carrying cameras, not bombs

978
00:53:58,591 --> 00:53:59,125
They're going to be shot at

979
00:53:59,225 --> 00:54:01,161
plain and simple

980
00:54:02,629 --> 00:54:04,664
I'm your political advisor

981
00:54:04,731 --> 00:54:08,301
I'm giving you a political analysis

982
00:54:08,401 --> 00:54:10,170
This is a set-up

983
00:54:10,804 --> 00:54:12,806
The Chiefs want to go in

984
00:54:12,872 --> 00:54:15,575
They need to redeem themselves
for the Bay of Pigs

985
00:54:15,708 --> 00:54:17,811
They gotta go in this time
and do it right

986
00:54:18,545 --> 00:54:20,246
I'm gonna protect those pilots

987
00:54:22,315 --> 00:54:24,851
They're boxing us in
with these rules of engagement

988
00:54:24,951 --> 00:54:26,553
If you agree and
one of our planes gets knocked down

989
00:54:26,653 --> 00:54:28,121
or one of the ships
won't stop fro inspection

990
00:54:28,221 --> 00:54:29,756
the Chiefs will have us by the balls

991
00:54:29,856 --> 00:54:31,991
and will force us to start shooting

992
00:54:32,091 --> 00:54:33,993
They want a war

993
00:54:37,297 --> 00:54:41,367
and they're arranging thing to get one

994
00:54:43,703 --> 00:54:45,338
How does a man get to a place

995
00:54:45,405 --> 00:54:49,542
where he can say
"Throw those lives away" so easily?

996
00:54:49,676 --> 00:54:51,411
Maybe it's harder for them
to say than they let on

997
00:54:51,478 --> 00:54:52,212
but at the very least

998
00:54:52,278 --> 00:54:55,181
they believe it's in our best interest

999
00:54:55,281 --> 00:54:57,383
And you know what?

1000
00:54:57,517 --> 00:55:00,086
At the end of the day they may well

1001
00:55:00,220 --> 00:55:01,721
end up being right

1002
00:55:06,826 --> 00:55:07,560
I'll tell you one thing

1003
00:55:07,627 --> 00:55:09,095
We have to triple-check

1004
00:55:09,229 --> 00:55:13,633
everything the Chiefs say to us
with the guys that actually do it

1005
00:55:13,733 --> 00:55:14,601
And nobody's to know about this

1006
00:55:14,701 --> 00:55:16,369
but Bobby

1007
00:55:16,469 --> 00:55:19,105
I need redundant control over
what happens out there

1008
00:55:19,205 --> 00:55:20,173
If things aren't advertised

1009
00:55:20,240 --> 00:55:21,174
then you are gonna make sure
they come out the way I want

1010
00:55:21,274 --> 00:55:24,544
Starting with
this low-level flight thing

1011
00:55:25,011 --> 00:55:26,112
That's gonna be tough

1012
00:55:26,246 --> 00:55:28,815
You know how these guys are
about their chains of command

1013
00:55:29,382 --> 00:55:30,884
Listen, tell them
those chains of command

1014
00:55:30,950 --> 00:55:32,719
end at one place - me

1015
00:55:35,855 --> 00:55:37,190
Go ahead, sir

1016
00:55:37,357 --> 00:55:38,892
Speak up, lady. I cannot hear you

1017
00:55:39,025 --> 00:55:42,429
I got a train to catch
and I'd like to be home by Christmas

1018
00:55:42,562 --> 00:55:43,963
That's the one

1019
00:55:44,063 --> 00:55:44,998
What's her name?

1020
00:55:45,131 --> 00:55:46,232
Margaret

1021
00:55:47,233 --> 00:55:48,568
Margaret

1022
00:55:50,470 --> 00:55:52,338
Yes sir, I understand exactly
what you're talking about

1023
00:55:52,439 --> 00:55:53,773
I speak the language, too

1024
00:55:53,840 --> 00:55:54,774
What?

1025
00:55:54,841 --> 00:55:56,943
Margaret, would you mind
helping me with something?

1026
00:55:57,043 --> 00:55:58,812
What do you need, honey?

1027
00:55:58,912 --> 00:56:00,980
That tone of voice, specifically

1028
00:56:02,582 --> 00:56:04,918
What tone of voice?
What the hell is he talking about?

1029
00:56:05,051 --> 00:56:07,086
I told you, sir
I'm sorry, you're outta here

1030
00:56:12,625 --> 00:56:14,127
Ready Room

1031
00:56:14,561 --> 00:56:16,196
Skipper. What are you doing?

1032
00:56:16,329 --> 00:56:17,430
Looking out the door

1033
00:56:17,497 --> 00:56:18,498
I'll get him for you

1034
00:56:18,565 --> 00:56:19,365
At what?

1035
00:56:19,466 --> 00:56:20,200
Cuba

1036
00:56:20,333 --> 00:56:21,634
Skipper!

1037
00:56:21,734 --> 00:56:22,969
Telephone

1038
00:56:29,175 --> 00:56:29,843
Commander Ecker

1039
00:56:29,976 --> 00:56:30,944
Commander Ecker

1040
00:56:31,111 --> 00:56:32,812
This is the White House Operator

1041
00:56:32,912 --> 00:56:33,746
Please hold

1042
00:56:33,813 --> 00:56:34,814
Shit

1043
00:56:34,914 --> 00:56:38,017
Honey, you don't know what shit is

1044
00:56:38,685 --> 00:56:40,019
Commander

1045
00:56:40,086 --> 00:56:41,521
my name's Ken O'Donnell

1046
00:56:41,621 --> 00:56:43,256
Special Assistant to the President

1047
00:56:43,423 --> 00:56:44,324
Yes, sir

1048
00:56:44,457 --> 00:56:47,527
The Presiden'ts instructed me
to pass along an order to you

1049
00:56:47,627 --> 00:56:50,396
You are not to get shot down

1050
00:56:51,030 --> 00:56:52,365
We'll do our best, sir

1051
00:56:52,499 --> 00:56:54,300
I don't think
you understand me, Commander

1052
00:56:54,400 --> 00:56:56,202
You are not to get shot down

1053
00:56:56,269 --> 00:56:57,604
under any circumstances

1054
00:56:58,772 --> 00:56:59,572
Whatever happens up there

1055
00:56:59,606 --> 00:57:00,807
you were not shot at

1056
00:57:00,874 --> 00:57:02,308
Mechanical failures are fine

1057
00:57:02,375 --> 00:57:04,310
crashing into mountains, fine

1058
00:57:04,410 --> 00:57:08,181
You are not to be shot at, fired at

1059
00:57:08,248 --> 00:57:09,649
or launched upon

1060
00:57:09,749 --> 00:57:12,252
Excuse me, sir
What the hell is going on here?

1061
00:57:12,352 --> 00:57:14,154
Commander, if you are fired upon

1062
00:57:14,254 --> 00:57:17,190
the President will be forced to
attack the sites that fired upon you

1063
00:57:17,624 --> 00:57:18,992
He doesn't want to have to do that

1064
00:57:19,526 --> 00:57:21,828
It's very important that he doesn't

1065
00:57:21,928 --> 00:57:23,663
or things could go
very badly out of control

1066
00:57:23,730 --> 00:57:25,231
What about my men?

1067
00:57:25,365 --> 00:57:27,600
If we don't have anybody to protect us

1068
00:57:27,700 --> 00:57:28,935
I'm gonna be writing
letters home for parents

1069
00:57:29,068 --> 00:57:30,503
If the President
protects you, Commander

1070
00:57:30,603 --> 00:57:34,107
he may have to do it with the Bomb

1071
00:57:34,707 --> 00:57:37,911
I've known the man for fifteen years
The problem is

1072
00:57:38,044 --> 00:57:39,946
he will protect you

1073
00:57:40,079 --> 00:57:43,216
So I'm asking you
don't make him protect you

1074
00:57:43,316 --> 00:57:45,018
Don't get shot at

1075
00:57:45,952 --> 00:57:48,655
Okay, Mr. O'Donnell
We'll do what we can

1076
00:57:49,289 --> 00:57:50,723
I know you will

1077
00:57:51,758 --> 00:57:53,393
Good luck

1078
00:58:01,267 --> 00:58:02,368
Hey, Joey

1079
00:58:16,649 --> 00:58:17,050
See you, Joey

1080
00:58:17,150 --> 00:58:18,685
Thanks, Joey

1081
00:58:18,751 --> 00:58:20,587
There you go, Jeremy

1082
00:58:20,653 --> 00:58:21,387
Hey, Bruce

1083
00:58:21,454 --> 00:58:22,856
Skipper?

1084
00:58:22,989 --> 00:58:24,357
Never mind. Just do what I do

1085
00:58:24,491 --> 00:58:25,859
Hand signs only

1086
00:58:38,238 --> 00:58:39,005
You are clear

1087
00:58:39,072 --> 00:58:40,106
Ready to go, sir

1088
00:58:40,173 --> 00:58:41,741
Good luck, Skipper

1089
01:00:54,441 --> 01:00:55,775
Shit!

1090
01:00:55,842 --> 01:00:57,310
Did you see it?

1091
01:01:00,280 --> 01:01:01,714
Man! You were lucky, Skipper!

1092
01:01:01,781 --> 01:01:03,450
Danm sparrows

1093
01:01:03,550 --> 01:01:04,918
Musta been migrating

1094
01:01:05,018 --> 01:01:05,819
Sparrows?

1095
01:01:05,919 --> 01:01:07,253
Probably hit a couple hundred of them

1096
01:01:07,353 --> 01:01:08,721
How many did you hit, Bruce?

1097
01:01:08,822 --> 01:01:10,857
Sparrows?

1098
01:01:13,259 --> 01:01:15,061
A few, I guess

1099
01:01:15,528 --> 01:01:17,630
These 20 millimeter
or 40 millimeter sparrows, sir?

1100
01:01:17,730 --> 01:01:19,399
Those are bird strikes

1101
01:01:19,532 --> 01:01:21,868
Sparrows, to be precise

1102
01:01:22,335 --> 01:01:23,903
That's the way it is, guys

1103
01:01:24,637 --> 01:01:26,239
Get that film packed up!

1104
01:01:30,877 --> 01:01:31,911
Commander Ecker

1105
01:01:31,978 --> 01:01:32,579
Hello?

1106
01:01:32,679 --> 01:01:33,313
Sir

1107
01:01:33,413 --> 01:01:34,013
Commander

1108
01:01:34,080 --> 01:01:35,315
Mr. O'Donnell, I've been ordered

1109
01:01:35,415 --> 01:01:37,717
to deliver the film
to the Pentagon personally

1110
01:01:37,784 --> 01:01:39,085
What's going on here?

1111
01:01:39,219 --> 01:01:41,855
The Chiefs must wanna talk to you

1112
01:01:42,288 --> 01:01:44,157
They're gonna want to know
if you were fired on

1113
01:01:44,290 --> 01:01:45,125
Were you?

1114
01:01:45,258 --> 01:01:47,293
You could say that, sir

1115
01:01:51,064 --> 01:01:53,099
Commander, listen to me

1116
01:01:53,166 --> 01:01:57,971
I know this must fly in the face
of everything you've come to serve

1117
01:01:58,004 --> 01:02:01,007
but I'm asking you to look
through this to the other side

1118
01:02:04,110 --> 01:02:06,045
Commander William B. Ecker
reporting as ordered

1119
01:02:06,112 --> 01:02:06,946
Commander

1120
01:02:07,013 --> 01:02:07,814
Sir

1121
01:02:07,947 --> 01:02:09,516
Put your gear down over here

1122
01:02:10,817 --> 01:02:12,419
Would you like
a glass of water or anything?

1123
01:02:12,552 --> 01:02:13,820
No, thank you, sir

1124
01:02:14,888 --> 01:02:15,455
Sir

1125
01:02:15,588 --> 01:02:16,156
Ecker

1126
01:02:16,256 --> 01:02:18,158
Have a seat

1127
01:02:21,060 --> 01:02:23,329
Commander
I assume you know why you're here

1128
01:02:23,463 --> 01:02:24,397
Son

1129
01:02:24,531 --> 01:02:26,733
I wanna know just one thing

1130
01:02:26,833 --> 01:02:30,103
Did those bastards shoot so much
as a BB gun at you?

1131
01:02:33,039 --> 01:02:34,674
It was a cakewalk, sir

1132
01:02:36,709 --> 01:02:37,377
Mr. President

1133
01:02:37,510 --> 01:02:39,846
The OAS meeting starts
in less than an hour

1134
01:02:39,946 --> 01:02:41,848
Good. I think we need this one. Dean

1135
01:02:41,981 --> 01:02:43,850
We can't expect miracles

1136
01:02:43,950 --> 01:02:47,687
The quarantine is legal
if we get a mandate

1137
01:02:47,821 --> 01:02:49,389
Otherwise it's an act of war
in the eyes of the world

1138
01:02:49,522 --> 01:02:51,257
So you gotta get me the vote

1139
01:02:51,357 --> 01:02:52,492
And make it unanimous

1140
01:02:52,625 --> 01:02:54,027
Mr. President
the Organization of American States

1141
01:02:54,160 --> 01:02:55,228
hasn't had a unanimous vote since...

1142
01:02:55,328 --> 01:02:57,163
Unanimous, Dean

1143
01:03:23,490 --> 01:03:25,458
In accordance
with this afternoon's vote

1144
01:03:25,558 --> 01:03:27,660
at the Organization of American States

1145
01:03:27,761 --> 01:03:30,029
the quarantine
will hereby be effective

1146
01:03:30,163 --> 01:03:32,165
as of ten o'clock tomorrow morning

1147
01:03:48,281 --> 01:03:49,349
At eight a. m. this morning

1148
01:03:49,482 --> 01:03:51,618
the United States

1149
01:03:51,684 --> 01:03:54,521
detonated a hydrogen bomb above
Johnston Island in the South Pacific

1150
01:03:54,621 --> 01:03:57,490
The blast was quickly condemned
by the Soviet Union

1151
01:03:57,657 --> 01:04:01,261
who called upon all nations
to denounce the United States

1152
01:04:01,327 --> 01:04:02,695
for bringing the world
to the brink of destruction

1153
01:04:02,762 --> 01:04:04,230
Who the hell authorized the test?

1154
01:04:04,297 --> 01:04:05,598
What is this gonna say
to the Russians?

1155
01:04:05,732 --> 01:04:07,400
They look warlike?

1156
01:04:07,467 --> 01:04:09,302
Jesus Christ
we're lighting off nuclear weapons

1157
01:04:09,402 --> 01:04:11,104
like it's our own
private Fourth of July

1158
01:04:11,204 --> 01:04:12,038
You know what?

1159
01:04:12,172 --> 01:04:15,642
We should have brought in the guys
from the Atomic Energy Commission

1160
01:04:15,775 --> 01:04:17,477
and talked this through

1161
01:04:17,577 --> 01:04:20,113
Looked at these tests a little harder

1162
01:04:20,213 --> 01:04:22,282
before just giving the go-ahead

1163
01:04:24,584 --> 01:04:28,154
You know, last summer I read a book
"The Guns of August"

1164
01:04:28,788 --> 01:04:31,624
I wish every man on that blockade line
had read that book

1165
01:04:31,691 --> 01:04:32,759
It's World War One

1166
01:04:32,892 --> 01:04:34,694
There's thirteen million killed

1167
01:04:34,794 --> 01:04:36,129
It's all because the militaries
of both alliances believed

1168
01:04:36,262 --> 01:04:39,032
that they were so highly
attuned to one another's movements

1169
01:04:39,099 --> 01:04:41,935
and dispositions, they could
predict one another's intentions

1170
01:04:42,001 --> 01:04:44,370
But all their theories
were based on the last war

1171
01:04:44,471 --> 01:04:46,239
And the world
and technology had changed

1172
01:04:46,306 --> 01:04:48,641
and those lessons
were no longer valid

1173
01:04:48,708 --> 01:04:50,009
But it was all they knew

1174
01:04:50,143 --> 01:04:52,178
so the orders went out

1175
01:04:52,278 --> 01:04:54,180
couldn't be rescinded

1176
01:04:56,916 --> 01:04:58,985
The man in the field, his family
at home, they couldn't even tell

1177
01:04:59,052 --> 01:05:01,254
the reasons
why their lives were being destroyed

1178
01:05:04,657 --> 01:05:06,726
But why couldn't they stop it?

1179
01:05:07,494 --> 01:05:08,828
What could they have done?

1180
01:05:09,729 --> 01:05:11,731
Here we are 50 years later

1181
01:05:12,766 --> 01:05:15,969
Say one of their ships
resists the inspection

1182
01:05:16,102 --> 01:05:17,871
and we shoot out its rudder

1183
01:05:18,004 --> 01:05:19,572
and board

1184
01:05:19,672 --> 01:05:23,309
They shoot down
one of our planes in response

1185
01:05:23,443 --> 01:05:27,514
So we bomb their anti-aircraft sites
in response to that

1186
01:05:27,580 --> 01:05:29,416
They attack Berlin

1187
01:05:31,484 --> 01:05:33,253
So we invade Cuba

1188
01:05:36,156 --> 01:05:38,191
And they fire their missiles

1189
01:05:49,269 --> 01:05:52,505
Helen, I want you
to keep the kids close tomorrow

1190
01:05:53,173 --> 01:05:55,442
I want you to leave the TV on

1191
01:05:55,575 --> 01:05:58,311
I want you to sleep with it on
in the bedroom

1192
01:05:58,478 --> 01:06:00,880
until I call you
and tell you can turn it off

1193
01:06:01,014 --> 01:06:03,083
What's happened?

1194
01:06:03,183 --> 01:06:04,617
Nothing

1195
01:06:04,751 --> 01:06:07,420
you don't already know about

1196
01:06:07,520 --> 01:06:10,056
Just have the car ready to go
in case I call

1197
01:06:10,123 --> 01:06:12,625
or a Civil Defense Warning comes on

1198
01:06:13,293 --> 01:06:15,061
What happens to you?

1199
01:06:16,029 --> 01:06:18,131
I'm not leaving without you

1200
01:06:19,466 --> 01:06:22,469
I'll be evacuated with the President

1201
01:06:25,138 --> 01:06:26,539
Great

1202
01:06:29,576 --> 01:06:32,879
And while you're under a rock
somewhere with the President

1203
01:06:32,979 --> 01:06:34,414
what am I supposed to do
with our five children, Kenny?

1204
01:06:34,514 --> 01:06:35,515
Honey

1205
01:06:35,648 --> 01:06:38,551
We're not gonna let it come to that

1206
01:06:38,852 --> 01:06:40,320
I promise

1207
01:06:40,987 --> 01:06:43,590
Jack and Bobby

1208
01:06:43,990 --> 01:06:45,759
they're smart guys

1209
01:06:48,762 --> 01:06:50,497
You're smart, too

1210
01:06:54,567 --> 01:06:56,469
Not like them

1211
01:07:02,609 --> 01:07:03,977
Hi, Ken

1212
01:07:09,649 --> 01:07:13,586
Helen just asked me what arrangements
we have for the families

1213
01:07:13,653 --> 01:07:15,989
I just checked that myself

1214
01:07:16,022 --> 01:07:18,291
They're being issued identity cards

1215
01:07:18,425 --> 01:07:19,526
And if the call comes

1216
01:07:19,659 --> 01:07:23,363
evacuation officers meet them
at pre-arranged departure areas

1217
01:07:23,463 --> 01:07:25,231
They go by helicopter to Mount Weather

1218
01:07:25,331 --> 01:07:27,000
We meet them there

1219
01:07:31,104 --> 01:07:33,773
Course that's for morale

1220
01:07:33,940 --> 01:07:36,176
Missiles only take five minutes
to get here

1221
01:07:40,146 --> 01:07:42,449
The President
has asked Jackie and the children

1222
01:07:42,549 --> 01:07:45,552
to come back from the country
to be with him

1223
01:07:47,187 --> 01:07:49,322
You know those pictures upstairs...

1224
01:07:49,923 --> 01:07:51,458
of Lincoln?

1225
01:07:52,959 --> 01:07:55,361
He looked so old near the end

1226
01:07:56,963 --> 01:07:58,398
When we got here, I said

1227
01:07:58,531 --> 01:08:01,401
it's not gonna happen to us

1228
01:08:01,468 --> 01:08:03,636
We were too young

1229
01:08:04,704 --> 01:08:06,906
Why don't you go home tonight?

1230
01:08:07,941 --> 01:08:09,209
Go on home

1231
01:08:10,410 --> 01:08:11,711
Nah

1232
01:08:11,778 --> 01:08:13,913
It's too much trouble to get a car

1233
01:08:14,013 --> 01:08:16,950
Ken, we can get you a car
in 15 minutes

1234
01:08:17,050 --> 01:08:17,450
No

1235
01:08:17,584 --> 01:08:19,119
Go ahead

1236
01:08:19,185 --> 01:08:20,587
No

1237
01:08:20,920 --> 01:08:22,655
I'll let her sleep

1238
01:08:24,758 --> 01:08:26,659
I'll let 'em sleep

1239
01:08:27,160 --> 01:08:30,196
It almost seemed today as
if time stood still

1240
01:08:30,263 --> 01:08:32,165
The shooting hadn't started yet

1241
01:08:32,298 --> 01:08:34,067
but there weren't any
really encouraging signs

1242
01:08:34,167 --> 01:08:36,302
that it could be avoided

1243
01:08:36,369 --> 01:08:39,506
But worried, alarmed
afraid perhaps even...

1244
01:08:39,606 --> 01:08:42,108
the American public nonetheless

1245
01:08:42,175 --> 01:08:43,877
appeared determined and resolved

1246
01:08:45,712 --> 01:08:46,780
This is Walter Cronkite

1247
01:08:46,880 --> 01:08:47,514
Good night

1248
01:10:30,016 --> 01:10:30,884
Gentlemen

1249
01:10:31,017 --> 01:10:32,252
can you hear me?

1250
01:10:32,318 --> 01:10:34,187
Yes, we hear you fine

1251
01:10:34,354 --> 01:10:36,589
I've got one minute 'til ten here

1252
01:10:36,723 --> 01:10:40,126
The quarantine commences in one minute

1253
01:10:45,331 --> 01:10:47,400
And no sign of them stopping

1254
01:11:02,515 --> 01:11:04,050
Sir

1255
01:11:11,491 --> 01:11:13,726
The quarantine is now in effect

1256
01:11:14,260 --> 01:11:18,098
And it looks like our first customers
are the Gagarin and Kimovsk

1257
01:11:36,916 --> 01:11:39,819
Chief, I've got something
at zero three zero

1258
01:11:40,653 --> 01:11:43,189
XO, take a look at this

1259
01:11:46,192 --> 01:11:47,794
New contact, Skipper

1260
01:11:54,801 --> 01:11:56,102
What do we got?

1261
01:11:56,202 --> 01:11:58,104
A Russian sub

1262
01:12:00,173 --> 01:12:09,082
General Quarters!
All hands, man your battle stations

1263
01:12:13,453 --> 01:12:17,390
Breaker 231, correlates
to our Submarine at 9, 000 yards

1264
01:12:21,828 --> 01:12:23,930
It's protecting the freighters

1265
01:12:32,539 --> 01:12:36,076
Bob, is there any way to
avoid stopping the submarine first?

1266
01:12:36,176 --> 01:12:37,977
I'm afraid not, Mr. President

1267
01:12:38,111 --> 01:12:41,114
The sub has positioned itself between
the Pierce and the Soviet ships

1268
01:12:41,181 --> 01:12:42,982
Admiral Anderson insists
it's too much of a risk

1269
01:12:43,083 --> 01:12:44,517
to proceed with
stopping the freighters

1270
01:12:44,651 --> 01:12:47,053
The Pierce would be
a sitting duck for the sub

1271
01:12:48,488 --> 01:12:49,656
Put me through to the Pierce

1272
01:12:49,789 --> 01:12:50,590
Yes, sir

1273
01:12:50,657 --> 01:12:51,891
Admiral Anderson

1274
01:12:51,991 --> 01:12:55,295
the President wishes to speak
directly to the Captain of the Pierce

1275
01:12:55,762 --> 01:12:57,130
Is that a problem?

1276
01:12:57,230 --> 01:12:58,965
No, it isn't, sir

1277
01:12:59,766 --> 01:13:01,668
He's putting you through, sir

1278
01:13:01,801 --> 01:13:03,536
Sir, I'm patching you
through to the bridge now

1279
01:13:05,638 --> 01:13:07,107
This is the Captain of the Pierce

1280
01:13:07,173 --> 01:13:09,209
Captain
this is the President speaking

1281
01:13:09,309 --> 01:13:10,376
Mr. President

1282
01:13:10,477 --> 01:13:13,079
Is there any way you can
force that sub to the surface

1283
01:13:13,179 --> 01:13:15,315
without damaging it or yourself?

1284
01:13:15,448 --> 01:13:16,983
I can bring it up, Mr. President

1285
01:13:17,050 --> 01:13:19,853
But whether it's damaged or not
is up to the sub

1286
01:13:19,953 --> 01:13:21,755
Even if they do force it up

1287
01:13:21,855 --> 01:13:24,324
that sub'll be inspected
over the crew's dead bodies

1288
01:13:24,390 --> 01:13:27,427
They'd be executed for allowing it
when they got home

1289
01:13:39,272 --> 01:13:40,740
Captain, force the sub to the surface

1290
01:13:40,874 --> 01:13:42,409
Yes, Mr. President

1291
01:13:43,877 --> 01:13:44,978
Prepare to fire torpedoes

1292
01:13:45,078 --> 01:13:46,446
Prepare to fire torpedoes. Aye, sir

1293
01:13:46,546 --> 01:13:47,414
Prepare to launch ASROC

1294
01:13:47,447 --> 01:13:48,915
Prepare to launch ASROC! Aye, sir

1295
01:14:17,744 --> 01:14:19,446
What're they up to?

1296
01:14:21,281 --> 01:14:22,649
Slowing down

1297
01:14:30,790 --> 01:14:32,992
They stopped

1298
01:14:33,126 --> 01:14:33,793
Mr. Secretary!

1299
01:14:33,927 --> 01:14:36,563
We're receiving reports
the Russian ships are stopping

1300
01:14:36,696 --> 01:14:37,497
Mr. President

1301
01:14:37,564 --> 01:14:39,432
Reports are coming in here
to the Pentagon that

1302
01:14:39,566 --> 01:14:41,401
the ships appear to b stopping

1303
01:14:41,568 --> 01:14:43,403
Captain, belay that order!

1304
01:14:43,470 --> 01:14:44,404
Hold you fire!

1305
01:14:44,504 --> 01:14:45,305
Where's that coming from?

1306
01:14:45,371 --> 01:14:46,573
One second, Mr. President

1307
01:14:46,639 --> 01:14:49,175
Somebody find out what's going on

1308
01:14:52,078 --> 01:14:54,114
Those ships are definitely stopping

1309
01:14:56,182 --> 01:14:57,951
Some are turning around

1310
01:15:00,186 --> 01:15:01,087
Are they stopping?

1311
01:15:01,221 --> 01:15:02,122
I don't know what they're doing

1312
01:15:02,255 --> 01:15:03,556
Admiral

1313
01:15:03,723 --> 01:15:04,958
Admiral, what's happening?

1314
01:15:05,024 --> 01:15:06,993
Yes, sir. They are... stopping

1315
01:15:08,495 --> 01:15:09,796
Mr. President

1316
01:15:09,863 --> 01:15:11,698
reports are coming in from all around

1317
01:15:11,831 --> 01:15:14,567
The ships are stopping

1318
01:15:14,667 --> 01:15:16,503
Some are turning around

1319
01:15:16,603 --> 01:15:19,139
Soem are turning around

1320
01:15:28,248 --> 01:15:31,918
We were eyeball to eyeball, and I
think the other fellow just blinked

1321
01:15:47,767 --> 01:15:49,235
Sir

1322
01:15:49,335 --> 01:15:51,538
Mr. President

1323
01:15:51,604 --> 01:15:53,139
Sir?

1324
01:15:53,273 --> 01:15:55,375
We have the tally from NSA

1325
01:15:55,442 --> 01:15:57,977
We have 20 ships
stopping and/or turning around

1326
01:15:58,111 --> 01:16:01,114
Six, however
appear to be continuing for the line

1327
01:16:04,250 --> 01:16:06,953
It's a mistake

1328
01:16:06,986 --> 01:16:09,923
They must not have gotten
their orders yet. Let 'em go

1329
01:16:09,989 --> 01:16:11,791
That's unlikely, Bobby

1330
01:16:11,891 --> 01:16:13,359
We've been monitoring
the radio transmissions

1331
01:16:13,460 --> 01:16:15,295
from the Gagarin and the Kimovsk

1332
01:16:15,361 --> 01:16:17,831
Their radios are working
just fine, Mr. President

1333
01:16:17,997 --> 01:16:21,000
One ship, an accident, maybe

1334
01:16:21,167 --> 01:16:23,303
Six, Mr. President, is intentional

1335
01:16:23,403 --> 01:16:24,771
Mr. President, let them go

1336
01:16:24,838 --> 01:16:25,939
You're still here?

1337
01:16:26,039 --> 01:16:29,609
